710357f.text:
Ninth Avenue, at West 29th Street, showing the terminus of the Greenwich Street 9 Ninth Avenue Elevated Railroad and one of its cars. This is the experimental line using a wire cable as the means of power. Steam locomotion replaced this later. The station is at the N.E. corner. For additional views see Greenwich Street at Dey Street, and Ninth Avenue at Gansevoort Street.
1867-8
Gift of Major Quinn

710358f-a.text:
Ninth Avenue (Foreground of No. 1 and not seen), at the N.W. corner of west 29th Street, (left) showing the "Milk Sheds" of the New York Central Railroad. These occupy the entire block bounued by 29th and 30th Streets; and Ninth and Tenth Avenues. In the Spring of 1931 they will be razed for the new Parcel Post office of the Post Office. Steel for same will rise in February
1932.
Views 2 and 3 show the southerly side of the yards (north side of 29th Street) and tenements on 10th Avenue. At the right are buildings on the north side of West 30th Street.
View 1: Sept. 8, 1930
Views 2-3 Jan. 25,1930
P.L. Sperr

Ninth Avenue (across foreground from left to right)and enwirons, from WW. 29th (intersection at left) to 3O'Street (rimht), showing the New York Central Railroad milk shed and vards extending to Tenth Avenue. The photographer gives his vantage point as the French Hoapital which is on the south side of W. 5Oh Street between Eighth and Ninth Avenues and he is viewirg westward towards the North (Hudson) River and the Wersey Shore. A popular name for this area was "Nells Kitchen".
About Juhe 25, 1930.

Shown is the Parcel Post Office of the Post office being prepared (in No.l) and under improvement (No 2.). Upon this site formerly stood the "Milk Sheds" of the N.Y. entral Railroad. Note in the left background of View 2 the recently erected
Starrett-Lehigh Building.
View 1: April 10, 1931
View 2: Jan. 28, 1932
P. L. Sperr

730128f-a.text:
General View Midtown Manhattan, in the 30's: View 1 is southwestward from 42nd Street and Lexington Avenue. It shows the Belmont Hotel(right) and the Architects Building. In the background is the Empire State Building and to
its right the 10 East 40th Street Building.
View 2 is northwestward toward the Empire State, from West 29th Street and Ninth Avenue. On the extreme left is the Fifth Avenue Building, at 42nd Street.
April, 1931

P.L. Sperr

Views 1,2
